AIM:
To develop a simple Employee Management module using Spring Core that demonstrates Inversion of Control (IoC) and Dependency Injection (DI) using Spring annotations such as @Component and @Autowired. 
The module should use BeanFactory to manage beans and store employee data in memory.

PROCEDURE:

Create a Maven project and configure Spring Core by adding the spring-context dependency inside pom.xml.
Create the package structure (edu.Task_8) and add all required classes:
Employee.java
EmployeeRepository.java
EmployeeService.java
AppConfig.java
MainApp.java
Create the Employee model class with fields such as id, name, and department along with getters, setters, and a toString() method.
Develop EmployeeRepository and annotate it with @Component to enable Inversion of Control (IoC).
Use a HashMap for in-memory storage.
Implement methods such as save(), findById(), findAll(), and deleteById().
Develop EmployeeService and annotate it with @Component.
Use @Autowired for Dependency Injection (DI) to inject EmployeeRepository.
Implement business methods such as addEmployee(), getEmployee(), getAllEmployees(), removeEmployee().

Create AppConfig.java and enable component scanning using:

@Configuration  
@ComponentScan(basePackages = "edu.Task_8")
Use BeanFactory/ApplicationContext in MainApp
Load the Spring container using AnnotationConfigApplicationContext.
Retrieve the EmployeeService bean, demonstrating Spring IoC.
Add employees, fetch employees, delete records, and print results.
Run the application, observe the stored employees, and confirm DI, IoC, add/find/delete functionalities working properly.

